            <section id="specifications" class="content-section bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-700 mb-4">11kV & 33kV Cable Specifications</h2>
                <p class="mb-4 text-gray-700">This section details the technical specifications of 11kV and 33kV underground cables, primarily focusing on the Cross-Linked Polyethylene (XLPE) insulated types used by TAQA Distribution. You can explore various construction parameters and key electrical characteristics. An interactive table based on TAQA/ADDC/AADC Standard S-CAB-UMV-3CAL_00.DOCX allows you to delve into specific requirements. A chart also compares key differences between 11kV and 33kV cables.</p>
                
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-3">Predominant Cable Types</h3>
                <div class="accordion-item mb-2 border border-gray-200 rounded">
                    <button class="accordion-header w-full text-left p-3 bg-sky-50 hover:bg-sky-100 rounded-t font-medium">Cross-Linked Polyethylene (XLPE) Insulated Cables <span class="float-right">‚ñº</span></button>
                    <div class="accordion-content p-3 border-t border-gray-200 text-gray-600">
                        <p>XLPE is the standard for 11kV and 33kV cables due to superior dielectric properties, thermal performance (90¬∞C continuous, 250¬∞C short-circuit), mechanical strength, and resistance to moisture/chemicals. TAQA specifies three-core Aluminium conductor XLPE cables.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-item mb-4 border border-gray-200 rounded">
                    <button class="accordion-header w-full text-left p-3 bg-amber-50 hover:bg-amber-100 rounded-t font-medium">Paper Insulated Lead Covered (PILC) Cables <span class="float-right">‚ñº</span></button>
                    <div class="accordion-content p-3 border-t border-gray-200 text-gray-600">
                        <p>Legacy technology, may exist in older network sections. Transition joints between PILC and XLPE cables are points of vulnerability due to material incompatibilities and thermo-mechanical differences, requiring careful management.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-3">Key XLPE Cable Specifications (TAQA/ADDC/AADC)</h3>
